source: # COGS 108 - Final Project
# Overview

I started this project to see whether people would prefer to visit large parks to small parks, assuming that the amount of visitors to a park is proportional to the amount of Yelp reviews it gets. After my research, I conclude that there's a linear relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it gets. If I were to give advice to the park system of San Diego county, I would include the park size in my decision.

# Name & GitHub

- Name: Anh Pham
- GitHub Username: anh65498
# Research Question
Is there a linear relationship between the size of San Diego parks and the number of Yelp reviews that park get?
## Background and Prior Work

Although park visitors help generate the awareness and income to preserve the natural habitats, they can also throw off the balance of the existing ecosystems. A research by Johnson & Wales University [1] points out that all visitors have some degree of negative impact on the environments. Hence, understanding the factors that predict the patterns of visitor behavior in the park is crucial to mantain the current infrastructures, natural resources, and visitors experience. A study by Utah State University [2] found that resource-related factors, such as terrain, resource condition, presence of wildlife, etc., may influence visitor behavior more than visitor characteristics, such as education level, activity expertise, or familiarity with minimum-impact recreation practices. Another study published in the International Journal of Geo-Information [3] suggests that the higher the park budget, the more visitors it gets, and the higher the employee number, the fewer visitors it gets.

In this project, I want to find out if the size of the park can predict the amount of visitors it will get. Since it was challenging to find the exact data on the amount of visitors to San Diego parks, I use the amount of Yelp reviews of each park as a measurement of its popularity. Yelp is a popular website where users can post reviews for any business and public places, including parks. Even though Yelp is not completely reliable, as a study found that 20% of restaurant reviews in 2013 on the site is fake [4], public parks are non-profit so there is not point in writing fake reviews for them so we can trust the Yelp reviews on parks were written by real park visitors.

References (include links):
- [1] https://scholarsarchive.jwu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1006&context=student_scholarship
- [2] https://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=8294&context=etd
- [3] https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=&ved=2ahUKEwiz4O7s7tPtAhWzHzQIHe4CDc8QFjABegQIBxAC&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.mdpi.com%2F2220-9964%2F7%2F3%2F124%2Fpdf&usg=AOvVaw1RkXoakCa3zj7g7FnW4TCs
- [4] https://www.marketwatch.com/story/20-of-yelp-reviews-are-fake-2013-09-24
# Hypothesis

Personally, I always prefer to visit large parks than small parks because they are more entertaining and pretty. However, I can't generalize this preference to the public because there could be other factors that affect the popularity of a park. However, my hypothesis is that large parks will get more visitors than small parks. Since visitors will post Yelp reviews, large parks will get more Yelp reviews than small parks.
# Dataset(s)

- Dataset Name: yelp_SD_parks.csv

    + Link to the dataset: https://github.com/COGS108/individual_fa20/blob/master/data/yelp_SD_parks.csv
    
    + Number of observations: 834
    
    + Description: This file contains 834 San Diego park names, addresses, phone numbers, Yelp id, URL, Yelp star rating, review counts, longitude, latitude, whether it is closed or open.
    
    
- Dataset Name: parks_datasd.geojson

    + Link to the dataset: https://github.com/COGS108/individual_fa20/blob/master/data/parks_datasd.geojson
    
    + Number of observations: 2769
    
    + Description: This file contains 2769 San Diego park information. Each observation includes a short park name, long park name, number of acres calculated from polygon, type of park, location description, and ownership.
    

I will attempt to extract 834 park sizes (in acres) from `parks_datasd.geojson` and their corresponding Yelp review count from `yelp_SD_parks.csv` to see if there is a linear relationship between the size of the park and its rating.

# Data Cleaning

The datasets I found were already organized neatly in csv format and geojson format so importing them into Jupyter Notebook is easy. However, both of them have a lot of redundant, duplicate and incomplete observations that I have to remove. I only retain the park names, Yelp review count, and park size for the analysis.

To get the data into a usable format, I wrangle data from both the Yelp dataset and the Park geojson dataset. First, I imported 834 San Diego park information from the Yelp dataset. Then, drop unnecessary columns like address, phone, Yelp id, url, longitutde, latitude, and is_closed to increase the processing speed. After that, I drop observations with missing values and duplicates. From screening the data, I see that data appears to be in good quality but a few observations have the same park name and different location, and some have different reviews. To avoid confusion, I decide to drop the duplicate Yelp reviews with the same park name. After that, I sort the dataframe alphabetically by name so I can add a column for the park size that matches with the park name once I process data from the Park geojson dataset.

Then, I import 2769 San Diego park information, convert geodataframe to panda's dataframe, drop unnecessary columns and observations with missing values and duplicates. From screening the data, I see that data appears to be in good quality but a few observations have the same park name and different acres. I choose to only retain the first entry of the same park. Then, I sort the dataframe alphabetically by name. 

Finally, I combined both dataset into a single dataframe with matching park name, Yelp review count, and park size. I got 110 observation in the final dataframe to start my analysis.

After cleaning up the data, there are 109 observations left, each has its size (in acres) and the number of public Yelp reviews.
# Data Analysis & Results

### 1. EDA

Analyzing the distribution of my variables: park size (`gis_acres`) and the amount of Yelp reviews (`review_count`).

First, let's analyze `gis_acres`

plot = sns.distplot(merged_df["gis_acres"], kde=False)
plot.set_title('San Diego Park Size Distribution')
plot.set_ylabel('frequency')

f2 = plt.gcf()

We see that `gis_acres` does not have a clear distribution. However, most parks appears to be less than 100 acres. Perhaps if we cut out the outliers, we can see the distribution of park size. 

Let's analyze the data further by finding the median, max, min, IQR, and outliers of park size.

print(merged_df["gis_acres"].describe())
print("median", merged_df["gis_acres"].median())                        # 8.758857315

# determine the 25th and 75th percentiles
lower, upper = np.percentile(merged_df["gis_acres"], [25,75])      # (4.0398099125, 14.3426289675)

# calculate the outliers data
iqr = upper - lower
print("upper_cutoff", upper + 1.5 * iqr)               # 29.97914767375

The median of park size is 8.759 acres and 75% of the data is less 14.343 acres so parks are generally small but the max is so large that it skewed the distribution. A commonly used rule is that a data point is an outlier if it is more than 1.5 * IQR. 

Let's create a new dataframe, remove all the outlier parks who is larger than 30 acres, and plot the remaining data points to see if park size follows a normal distribution.

#### Let's analyze the distribution of the amount of Yelp reviews of each park with `review_count` variables

plot = sns.distplot(merged_df["review_count"], kde=False)

Let's analyze the data further by finding the median, max, min, IQR, and outliers of park Yelp review count.

print(merged_df["review_count"].describe())

The median of review count is between 15 and 16 reviews, 75% of the parks has less 48 reviews but the most popular park got 2105 reviews, which is so large that it skewed the distribution.

new_merged_df = merged_df[merged_df['review_count'] <= 111]
new_merged_df

# Draw the histogram plot 
plot = sns.distplot(new_merged_df["review_count"])
plot.set_title('San Diego Park Yelp Review Count')
plot.set_ylabel('frequency')

f2 = plt.gcf()

By observing the graph, the number of Yelp review of parks are very right-skewed and the majority of parks have less than 50 reviews. It is very right-skewed because there are 25% parks with more than 47 reviews but they are spread between 47 and 2105 reviews.

### 1. Analysis

Since I want to see if there is a linear relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it gets, I will carry out the Inferential Analysis.

First, I plot all the data I got after the data cleaning step, keeping all the outliers data.

sns.scatterplot(x='gis_acres', y="review_count", data=merged_df)
plt.xlabel("GIS acres")
plt.ylabel("Review Count")

From observation, there is no clear linear relationship between these park size and Yelp review count. I will still carry about the OSL analysis to make sure there is no linear relationship between them.

My null hypothesis (H0) is that there is no relationship between gis_acres and review_count.

My alternative hypothesis (Ha) is that there is a relationship between gis_acres and review_count.

# Using OLS to analyze the linear relationship
outcome, predictors = patsy.dmatrices('review_count ~ gis_acres', merged_df)
mod = sm.OLS(outcome, predictors)
res = mod.fit()
print(res.summary())

From OSL analysis, the p-value is 0.005. A p-value less than 0.05 (typically ≤ 0.05) indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis, and accept the alternative hypothesis.

Hence, there is a relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it get.

`review_count = 65.8229 + 0.1577 * gis_acres`

This is suspicious because this means the minimum number of reviews a park get is 65 reviews. Something is not right here.
In order to find a better conclusion, I decide to transform my data by applying log to it. Since both dataset are skewed, it is logical to use this approach

merged_df['review_count'] = np.log10(merged_df.review_count)
merged_df['gis_acres'] = np.log10(merged_df.gis_acres)

merged_df

sns.regplot(data=merged_df, x = "gis_acres", y = "review_count", ci = None)
ax = sns.scatterplot(x='gis_acres', y='review_count', data=merged_df)
ax.set_title('Relationship of Park Acres vs. Yelp Rating')
ax.set_xlabel('log(Acres)')
ax.set_ylabel('log(Rating)')

outcome, predictors = patsy.dmatrices('review_count ~ gis_acres', merged_df)
mod = sm.OLS(outcome, predictors)
res = mod.fit()
print(res.summary())

After transforming the data, the p-value is now 0.000, which we can conclude with great confidence that there is a relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it get.

`review_count = 0.8013 + 0.4282 * gis_acres`
# Ethics & Privacy

Both of the datasets I used in my research were obtained from Professor Shannon so I have permission to use them. They do not contain any private information of anyone or anything. A concern I have is that Yelp forbids data collecting but the dataset I used was collected by using Yelp API, a tool created by Yelp so the Yelp was ethically collected. The Park geojson dataset was collected from the San Diego government website so it was also ethically collected. Both datasets have no privacy concern.

There could be a bias in my dataset. Yelp reviews are written by people and people are bias. They may not choose to leave a Yelp comment at every park but only at review-worthy parks. They may forget to write Yelp reviews. Regardless of these biases, both of the dataset helped answered the research question.
# Conclusion & Discussion

After cleaning 2769 observations, I got 110 observations left to carry out the analysis. To my surpise, the initial OSL analysis before data transformation shows that there is a linear relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it has even though that relationship doesn't make sense. Although my p-value was within the range that indicate there is a relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it get, there are a few limitations in my research that may not warrant this finding.

First of all, both datasets I used have a lot of redundancy and duplication. There are a lot of parks with the same name but different park size, a few with the same name but different address. With the constraint of time, I choose to keep the first park that appeared in the dataset. Secondly, I only got 110 observations to work with, which is too little to produce good conclusion. I was expecting more from the combination of 834 and 2769 data points. Lastly, I didn't remove the outliers from the data that I use for OSL analysis so despite the reasonable p-value, my linear function is `review_count = 65.8229 + 0.1577 * gis_acres`, which is suspicious because that means the minimum number of reviews a park get is 65 reviews. From the EDA section, 75% of parks has less than 48 Yelp reviews. 

To correct my limitation, since my datasets were skewed, I applied log transformation. I end up with a more reasonable relationship between the park size and the amount of Yelp reviews it has. `review_count = 0.8013 + 0.4282 * gis_acres`

From my research, I found the linear relationship between park size and its Yelp review count. San Diego park system can use the park size or its popularity on Yelp to predict which park to pay more attention to.
